  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To these chief priests and Levites Ezra weighed the silver and the gold and the vessels; שׁקל, to weigh, i.e., to deliver by weight. In the Chethiv אשׁקולה the O sound is maintained, and consequently the Keri is pointed  -. On the other hand, in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the וּ is dropped, and the form pointed with  -, though many MSS, followed by J. H. Michaelis, have ו- here also. אל בּית תּרוּמת is in apposition with the before-named objects: the gold, the silver, and the vessels, the offering for the house of our God, which the king, his councillors ... had offered; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ההרימוּ the article represents the relative pronoun; see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 26:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". הנּמצאים, all Israelites who were found, met with, in Babylon, and were not going with them to Jerusalem; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ידם על, like יד על, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to their hand, i.e., handed over to their keeping. The gifts amounted to: six hundred and fifty talents of silver, and silver vessels one hundred in talents, i.e., one hundred talents in value, one hundred talents of gold, and twenty covered basins of gold (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") one thousand dariks in value, and two brazen vessels of fine golden brilliancy, precious as gold. מצהב is an abstract noun, formed from the participle Hophal of צהב, to glitter like gold, and constructed as a feminine. The word, with its adjective, either depends upon נחשׁט, in the stat. construct., or stands in apposition thereto, and is not, as a participle Hophal, used adjectively and combined with נחשׁט, for then the two adjectives מצהב and טובה would not be in different genders. חמוּדות, like חמוּדות כּלי,   ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
